Just look at this class.

482
00:22:39.358 --> 00:22:41.384
You're all a bunch of dudes.

483
00:22:41.460 --> 00:22:43.224
Um. we're girls.

484
00:22:45.297 --> 00:22:46.822
That's awkward.

485
00:22:46.899 --> 00:22:48.333
(BELL RINGS)

486
00:22:48.834 --> 00:22:51.360
I'll cover all the dating
stuff in my next seminar.

487
00:22:51.437 --> 00:22:54.430
"Puberty: Monster or
Misunderstood Friend?"

488
00:22:55.474 --> 00:22:58.967
That kid I sent to the office
had some weird zit cream on.

489
00:22:59.044 --> 00:23:00.672
Professor Enrico.

490
00:23:01.247 --> 00:23:02.247
(LAUGHING)

491
00:23:04.717 --> 00:23:08.051
Guster. Burton Guster. You
interviewed me for admission.

492
00:23:08.120 --> 00:23:10.612
Math prodigy? I interview
people all the time.

493
00:23:10.689 --> 00:23:12.021
Was this recently?

494
00:23:12.091 --> 00:23:13.525
Semi-recent.

495
00:23:13.592 --> 00:23:14.992
Twenty years ago.

496
00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:18.030
But I tap-danced in trochaic
tetrameter. Made you wanna cry.

497
00:23:18.097 --> 00:23:20.259
That rings a bell.

498
00:23:20.332 --> 00:23:22.858
So. visiting the old alma mater?

499
00:23:23.636 --> 00:23:25.502
No. I went to public school.

500
00:23:25.571 --> 00:23:28.803
Really? I could've sworn I
recommended admission.

501
00:23:28.874 --> 00:23:33.039
Either way. I assume a person
with your skills ended up at JPL

502
00:23:33.112 --> 00:23:35.377
(CHUCKLING) or
some kind of think tank.

503
00:23:35.447 --> 00:23:39.282
Actually. I ended up
in pharmaceuticals.

504
00:23:39.351 --> 00:23:41.582
You know. curing stuff.

505
00:23:44.023 --> 00:23:46.254
Well. keep up the good work.

506
00:23:46.325 --> 00:23:48.317
Thank you.

507
00:23:48.394 --> 00:23:51.922
Dude. you didn't even
mention Magichead.

508
00:23:51.997 --> 00:23:53.590
Guys. we're freaking out.

509
00:23:53.732 --> 00:23:55.530
We're pretty sure
Professor Hahn is our guy.

510
00:23:55.601 --> 00:23:56.796
So turn him in to the cops.

511
00:23:56.869 --> 00:23:59.771
Not without proof. Know
anything about him?

512
00:23:59.838 --> 00:24:01.783
The only time we see him
is when he gets his espresso

513
00:24:01.807 --> 00:24:03.207
in the morning before homeroom.

514
00:24:03.275 --> 00:24:04.795
There's an espresso
bar here on campus?

515
00:24:04.843 --> 00:24:06.937
Wait! Wasn't Hahn
involved in that thing?

516
00:24:07.012 --> 00:24:08.036
You remember that thing?

517
00:24:08.113 --> 00:24:10.091
That thing with the other
thing? No. no. Just the first thing.

518
00:24:10.115 --> 00:24:12.494
From five years ago? When the
student attacked the professor?

519
00:24:12.518 --> 00:24:14.749
Oh. yeah. That could
have been Hahn.

520
00:24:14.820 --> 00:24:17.813
Some student attacked Hahn and he
made sure the headmaster expelled him.

521
00:24:17.890 --> 00:24:19.825
Who was the student
that attacked him?

522
00:24:22.027 --> 00:24:23.427
According to the
school computers.

523
00:24:23.495 --> 00:24:27.933
the only kid to be expelled in the
last 10 years was a Lester Baekeland.

524
00:24:33.405 --> 00:24:35.135
What are you doing?

525
00:24:35.207 --> 00:24:37.369
Getting the plague. apparently.

526
00:24:37.977 --> 00:24:39.343
God!

527
00:24:39.878 --> 00:24:43.815
Babcock. Babette.
Battra-something.

528
00:24:43.882 --> 00:24:46.249
Baekeland. God!

529
00:24:46.952 --> 00:24:47.976
(COUGHS)

530
00:24:48.053 --> 00:24:49.578
I see why you wanted
to go here. Gus.

531
00:24:49.655 --> 00:24:51.533
They keep meticulous records
of everything. just like you.

532
00:24:51.557 --> 00:24:52.557
Uh-huh.

533
00:24:52.624 --> 00:24:53.683
Expelled for cheating.

534
00:24:53.759 --> 00:24:56.354
Dude. there's a transcript of
his hearing. What does it say?

535
00:24:56.428 --> 00:24:59.762
Let's see. The kid claimed
Hahn busted him for cheating

536
00:24:59.832 --> 00:25:04.133
and tried to extort his scholarship
money from him to stay quiet.

537
00:25:04.203 --> 00:25:06.729
Hahn denies it.

538
00:25:06.805 --> 00:25:10.401
The headmaster. of course. sides
with the teacher. The kid gets expelled.

539
00:25:12.144 --> 00:25:13.144
Huh.

540
00:25:13.345 --> 00:25:15.974
That means Hahn
is a blackmailer.

541
00:25:16.048 --> 00:25:19.109
Maybe he threatened
the wrong person this time.

542
00:25:22.221 --> 00:25:23.280
Gus?

543
00:25:24.923 --> 00:25:26.016
Gus?

544
00:25:26.792 --> 00:25:28.488
I got in.

545
00:25:28.560 --> 00:25:31.120
I applied and I got in.

546
00:25:31.196 --> 00:25:32.459
That means a lot. buddy.

547
00:25:32.531 --> 00:25:35.501
You'd rather stay with your best
friend than. you know. have a future.

548
00:25:35.567 --> 00:25:36.567
No. Shawn.

549
00:25:36.635 --> 00:25:39.070
It says. "Parents of
applicant refused admission."

550
00:25:39.138 --> 00:25:41.573
If I had known I'd gotten
in. I would have been ghost.

551
00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:44.166
This place has a direct
line to the Ivy League.

552
00:25:44.243 --> 00:25:45.871
Why would my
parents turn it down?

553
00:25:45.944 --> 00:25:48.038
I don't know. Maybe it
was just too expensive.

554
00:25:48.113 --> 00:25:49.809
I could have gotten
financial aid. Shawn.

555
00:25:49.882 --> 00:25:51.976
Half the kids here are on
scholarships with stipends.

556
00:25:52.051 --> 00:25:53.461
Could we not obsess
about this right now?

557
00:25:53.485 --> 00:25:54.851
We do have a murder to prevent.

558
00:25:54.920 --> 00:25:56.411
I'm not obsessing. Shawn.

559
00:25:56.488 --> 00:25:59.534
I just found out that the course of my life
may have been changed by my parents.

560
00:25:59.558 --> 00:26:00.651
You've seen <i>Sliding Doors.</i>

561
00:26:00.726 --> 00:26:01.766
I most certainly have not.

562
00:26:01.827 --> 00:26:04.456
Yes. you did! Dude! I
have not seen <i>Sliding Doors.</i>

563
00:26:04.530 --> 00:26:06.931
It was me. you and Missy
Isaacs. What are you talking about?

564
00:26:06.999 --> 00:26:10.561
I'm talking about a Gwyneth Paltrow
vehicle that I know I never saw!

565
00:26:10.636 --> 00:26:12.264
GUS: Oh. please!

566
00:26:12.571 --> 00:26:15.040
I know you're home.
This is my fifth message.

567
00:26:15.107 --> 00:26:16.575
Call me back.

568
00:26:17.342 --> 00:26:19.709
They're just screening my
calls until I have to let this go.

569
00:26:19.778 --> 00:26:20.871
But it's not gonna happen.

570
00:26:20.946 --> 00:26:22.812
Gus. let's face it.

571
00:26:22.915 --> 00:26:25.976
Your parents thought splitting us
up at a young age was a mistake.

572
00:26:26.051 --> 00:26:27.246
And I can't say I blame them.

573
00:26:27.319 --> 00:26:28.947
For a while. I was
your only friend

574
00:26:29.021 --> 00:26:31.650
that wasn't imaginary or
an action figure of some kind.

575
00:26:31.723 --> 00:26:34.659
Shawn. if anything. my parents
wanted me to stay in public school

576
00:26:34.726 --> 00:26:37.025
so that I would stand out
compared to people like you.

577
00:26:37.096 --> 00:26:38.860
Yeah. no holes in that theory.

578
00:26:38.931 --> 00:26:41.628
I don't know which is worse.
my parents dodging my calls

579
00:26:41.700 --> 00:26:44.540
or you volunteering me to pick up
a murderer first thing in the morning.

580
00:26:44.603 --> 00:26:47.402
Dude. it is your turn
to drive the carpool.

581
00:26:47.473 --> 00:26:50.534
What's our plan?
Today is Murder Day.

582
00:26:50.609 --> 00:26:54.239
Speaking of Murder Day. is
that really what you're wearing?

583
00:26:54.313 --> 00:26:57.772
Shawn. in about two minutes. we're
gonna be in a confined space with a killer.

584
00:26:57.850 --> 00:26:59.409
Please tell me you
have a good reason.

585
00:26:59.485 --> 00:27:01.078
Of course I have a
good reason. Gus.

586
00:27:01.153 --> 00:27:03.247
This time it'll be
just you. me and him.

587
00:27:03.322 --> 00:27:06.053
and I will totally
break him down.

588
00:27:07.826 --> 00:27:09.818
GUS: That's Hahn's house.

589
00:27:17.536 --> 00:27:20.938
Or maybe it'll just
be you and me.

590
00:27:30.749 --> 00:27:35.449
Well. according to our arson
investigator. here is our murderer.

591
00:27:35.521 --> 00:27:37.888
Apparently. there was a
slight gas leak in the stove.

592
00:27:37.956 --> 00:27:39.549
Overnight. room
fills with natural gas.

593
00:27:39.625 --> 00:27:41.059
Coffee pot clicks
on in the morning.

594
00:27:41.126 --> 00:27:42.890
there's a spark and kaboom.

595
00:27:42.961 --> 00:27:46.022
No. I'm sensing it was
definitely more of a kablam.

596
00:27:50.202 --> 00:27:51.613
So you're saying
this was an accident?

597
00:27:51.637 --> 00:27:54.937
Arson investigator says
there's no sign of foul play.

598
00:27:55.007 --> 00:27:58.367
The only time we see him is when he gets
his espresso in the morning before homeroom.

599
00:27:58.877 --> 00:28:00.903
Wait. I'm having a vision.

600
00:28:00.979 --> 00:28:04.108
Hahn preferred Italian
coffee. Espresso.

601
00:28:04.183 --> 00:28:05.583
Why would he be
brewing coffee here

602
00:28:05.651 --> 00:28:07.916
if he was gonna get his
fix in the morning at school?

603
00:28:07.986 --> 00:28:10.285
I'm sensing our killer brought
the coffee machine here

604
00:28:10.355 --> 00:28:13.052
and used it as a detonator
after creating the gas leak.

605
00:28:13.125 --> 00:28:15.526
What killer. Spencer? Our
expert says it's an accident.

606
00:28:15.594 --> 00:28:18.826
I say murder. It's what drew
me to this wretched place.

607
00:28:18.897 --> 00:28:20.559
Talk to the girl who
makes the espresso.

608
00:28:20.632 --> 00:28:24.626
I usually don't do this. but I have
a strong sense she'll back this up.

609
00:28:24.703 --> 00:28:27.298
Hahn had a cup first
thing every morning.

610
00:28:27.372 --> 00:28:28.783
What do you call
those coffee people?

611
00:28:28.807 --> 00:28:31.504
They're not cashiers.
they're not waitresses.

612
00:28:31.577 --> 00:28:32.577
Barrista.

613
00:28:32.844 --> 00:28:36.303
Gus. if you don't know the
answer. don't make up words.

614
00:28:46.358 --> 00:28:48.725
Dude. Hahn was broke.

615
00:28:48.794 --> 00:28:50.456
No wonder he's a blackmailer.

616
00:28:50.529 --> 00:28:52.828
The due date for the payment
is the same as Murder Day.

617
00:28:52.898 --> 00:28:54.025
Coincidence?

618
00:28:54.099 --> 00:28:55.397
I think not.

619
00:28:58.370 --> 00:29:02.398
It was staticky. but we heard a deep
gravelly voice talking to their cousin.

620
00:29:03.075 --> 00:29:05.408
<i>Someone named Muriel.</i>

621
00:29:09.047 --> 00:29:11.312
We are so on this case now.

622
00:29:14.820 --> 00:29:16.049
Your call. O'Hara.

623
00:29:16.121 --> 00:29:17.714
Either it's an accident
and we're done.

624
00:29:17.789 --> 00:29:20.190
or it's a homicide and
there's a killer on the loose.

625
00:29:20.259 --> 00:29:22.421
I don't buy this accident
angle for a second.

626
00:29:22.494 --> 00:29:24.986
Those kids practically
said this would happen.

627
00:29:25.063 --> 00:29:26.964
Let's bring them
back in for questioning.

628
00:29:30.035 --> 00:29:34.336
If you confess now.
name your accomplices.

629
00:29:34.473 --> 00:29:37.500
I will let the DA know that
you cooperated and maybe.

630
00:29:37.576 --> 00:29:39.442
just maybe. no guarantees.

631
00:29:39.511 --> 00:29:42.743
just maybe. they'll
cut you a break.

632
00:29:50.555 --> 00:29:52.547
That's terrible. What?

633
00:29:52.624 --> 00:29:55.594
Am I scared? Am I quaking? No.

634
00:29:55.661 --> 00:29:58.028
That was what I
call lowercase mad.

635
00:29:58.096 --> 00:30:00.930
You need to be uppercase mad!

636
00:30:02.768 --> 00:30:05.670
Those strange kids
are in Interrogation B.

637
00:30:08.640 --> 00:30:10.871
Listen. O'Hara.

638
00:30:10.976 --> 00:30:13.445
Given your slightly
pedestrian performance

639
00:30:13.512 --> 00:30:16.380
and the fact that this has now
jumped to a straight-up homicide.

640
00:30:16.448 --> 00:30:17.746
maybe I should
take over as lead.

641
00:30:17.816 --> 00:30:19.182
But why? It's my case.

642
00:30:19.251 --> 00:30:22.278
Which was fine when it
was just kids telling tales.

643
00:30:22.354 --> 00:30:24.949
but there are certain nuances
involved in a murder investigation

644
00:30:25.023 --> 00:30:27.583
which require a more
experienced touch.

645
00:30:27.659 --> 00:30:30.322
Nuances the chief says
I'll learn by being primary.

646
00:30:30.395 --> 00:30:32.489
Yeah. but... But what?

647
00:30:32.564 --> 00:30:33.998
There was an explosion.

648
00:30:34.066 --> 00:30:36.058
I've never had a case
with an explosion before.

649
00:30:36.134 --> 00:30:38.160
I've had assault
and burglary cases.

650
00:30:38.236 --> 00:30:39.614
Once I even had a
murder by thermometer.

651
00:30:39.638 --> 00:30:41.436
but I've never had an explosion!

652
00:30:41.506 --> 00:30:43.117
I mean. come on. Haven't
you ever pictured yourself

653
00:30:43.141 --> 00:30:45.736
trying to outrun a fireball
down a dark tunnel?

654
00:30:45.811 --> 00:30:46.835
No.

655
00:30:51.883 --> 00:30:55.650
Obviously. due to recent events. we
are taking a closer look at everything

656
00:30:55.721 --> 00:30:59.123
surrounding the school. including
the statement you gave to us.

657
00:30:59.191 --> 00:31:02.787
You mean. when we predicted someone
was going to die today. and they did?

658
00:31:02.861 --> 00:31:04.489
Well. that and...

659
00:31:04.563 --> 00:31:05.826
Watch your mouth. kid.

660
00:31:05.897 --> 00:31:08.176
Okay. I you're not fooling anybody.
We know what's going on here.

661
00:31:08.200 --> 00:31:11.364
What he means is.

662
00:31:11.436 --> 00:31:13.648
please tell us again about the
phone call that you overheard.

663
00:31:13.672 --> 00:31:16.665
No. Tell us about your
relationship with Hahn!

664
00:31:16.742 --> 00:31:18.608
You little son of
a... Lassiter. stop!

665
00:31:18.677 --> 00:31:20.441
They're teenagers.

666
00:31:20.512 --> 00:31:21.512
We're sorry.

667
00:31:21.580 --> 00:31:23.913
Lesson 63. Do not
apologize to the perp.

668
00:31:23.982 --> 00:31:25.493
They're not perps.
You don't know that!

669
00:31:25.517 --> 00:31:26.728
You two aren't really acquainted

670
00:31:26.752 --> 00:31:28.983
with game theory or
prisoner's dilemma. are you?

671
00:31:29.087 --> 00:31:30.111
Huh?

672
00:31:30.188 --> 00:31:33.352
He means you two don't really
get the good cop-bad cop dyad.

673
00:31:33.425 --> 00:31:35.087
Are you guys. like. together?

674
00:31:35.160 --> 00:31:38.130
No. She's way out of
his league. But no ring.

675
00:31:38.196 --> 00:31:40.461
GODDARD: Given his
age. I'm guessing divorced?

676
00:31:40.532 --> 00:31:42.364
I... What?

677
00:31:42.434 --> 00:31:43.732
Ooh. Still can't talk about it.

678
00:31:43.802 --> 00:31:45.794
So it's relatively recent then.

679
00:31:45.871 --> 00:31:47.635
I'm betting separated.
not divorced.

680
00:31:47.706 --> 00:31:49.732
Did you ever just
listen to her problems

681
00:31:49.808 --> 00:31:51.367
rather than always
trying to solve 'em?

682
00:31:51.443 --> 00:31:53.121
No. you had to be the
big tough cop. didn't ya?

683
00:31:53.145 --> 00:31:55.114
You never let her inside.

684
00:31:57.749 --> 00:31:58.978
Here. You see this. brainiac?

685
00:31:59.050 --> 00:32:00.930
This is what's waiting
for you when you turn 18.

686
00:32:00.986 --> 00:32:04.218
You're gonna graduate and
get your diploma. and then bam!

687
00:32:04.289 --> 00:32:06.520
We're taking a trip
down to the docks.

688
00:32:06.591 --> 00:32:10.653
That doesn't look very intimidating
with. you know. the one arm.

689
00:32:13.131 --> 00:32:14.131
(INHALES DEEPLY)

690
00:32:27.179 --> 00:32:29.648
When did my house
become a daycare center?

691
00:32:29.714 --> 00:32:32.274
Dad. you've been bugging me
for months to fix your computer.

692
00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:33.928
I finally bring the
geek squad in to do it.

693
00:32:33.952 --> 00:32:35.978
and now you're gonna
give me a hard time?

694
00:32:36.054 --> 00:32:37.386
Thank you!

695
00:32:38.557 --> 00:32:40.458
Hahn had someone's
juvenile record.

696
00:32:40.525 --> 00:32:42.236
Maybe he dug up
something on our killer's past.

697
00:32:42.260 --> 00:32:44.354
which means we have to
hack into the juvie database.

698
00:32:44.429 --> 00:32:45.453
Yeah. I'm with you.

699
00:32:45.530 --> 00:32:47.241
except for the part about
coming to my dad's house.

700
00:32:47.265 --> 00:32:49.644
Well. according to the kids.
the hack-in may come back to us.

701
00:32:49.668 --> 00:32:52.069
Now the authorities will be
led to an antique computer

702
00:32:52.137 --> 00:32:53.400
purchased by a former cop.

703
00:32:53.472 --> 00:32:54.963
Can you say wild goose chase?

704
00:32:55.040 --> 00:32:57.168
Jeez. This computer is ancient.

705
00:32:57.242 --> 00:33:00.770
I didn't realize ColecoVision
was still in business.

706
00:33:00.846 --> 00:33:02.212
All right. I'm in.

707
00:33:02.280 --> 00:33:05.478
Muriel Juvenile
Hall/Halfway House.

708
00:33:05.550 --> 00:33:06.745
What am I looking for?

709
00:33:06.818 --> 00:33:11.119
I'm sensing our investigation
centers on the year 1991.

710
00:33:11.189 --> 00:33:12.452
'91?

711
00:33:12.524 --> 00:33:14.459
There's nothing but a
bunch of photos here.

712
00:33:14.626 --> 00:33:16.561
Click on the top right.

713
00:33:20.265 --> 00:33:22.076
That's that kid I sent
to the principal's office.

714
00:33:22.100 --> 00:33:23.295
Kirk Gödel.

715
00:33:23.368 --> 00:33:24.768
Why the hell is a
photo from today

716
00:33:24.836 --> 00:33:26.862
mixed in with photos from '91?

717
00:33:26.938 --> 00:33:30.431
It's not. This photo
was taken 15 years ago.

718
00:33:37.582 --> 00:33:39.278
I'm having a vision.

719
00:33:39.351 --> 00:33:41.582
<i>The Man from Snowy River.</i>

720
00:33:41.653 --> 00:33:43.815
<i>Eddie Macon's Run?</i>

721
00:33:44.456 --> 00:33:46.049
<i>Spartacus.</i> Kirk Douglas!

722
00:33:46.124 --> 00:33:48.787
Yes. See if there's a
student named Kirk.

723
00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:51.921
The registrar gave me
access to all their files.

724
00:33:51.997 --> 00:33:52.997
(SIGHS)

725
00:33:53.532 --> 00:33:55.194
It's perfectly normal. you know.

726
00:33:55.433 --> 00:33:57.993
What is? The anxiety
of being in charge.

727
00:33:58.069 --> 00:34:00.732
I can sense you have the weight
of the world on your shoulders.

728
00:34:00.805 --> 00:34:04.139
I just really want
to get this right.

729
00:34:04.209 --> 00:34:06.075
Oh. I've got something.

730
00:34:06.144 --> 00:34:07.612
Kirk Gödel.

731
00:34:08.613 --> 00:34:10.138
SHAWN: Gödel.

732
00:34:10.215 --> 00:34:13.583
That's almost pronounced like "girdle"
because of the omelet on the "O."

733
00:34:13.652 --> 00:34:15.120
I'm pretty sure
that's an umlaut.

734
00:34:15.186 --> 00:34:16.415
I've heard it both ways.

735
00:34:16.488 --> 00:34:18.252
Let's see. No juvenile record.

736
00:34:18.323 --> 00:34:20.952
Only child. All stats match
up with his school records.

737
00:34:21.026 --> 00:34:22.494
Nothing out of the ordinary.

738
00:34:22.561 --> 00:34:23.756
Let's see what Google says.

739
00:34:23.828 --> 00:34:26.525
Search it with the word Muriel.

740
00:34:27.899 --> 00:34:31.267
Oh. here's an article from
the <i>Muriel County Newsletter.</i>

741
00:34:31.336 --> 00:34:34.738
According to this article.
Kirk Gödel and his parents

742
00:34:34.806 --> 00:34:37.640
died five years
ago in a car crash.

743
00:34:37.709 --> 00:34:39.429
There should be a
death certificate on file.

744
00:34:39.477 --> 00:34:41.036
but there's no sign of it.

745
00:34:41.112 --> 00:34:43.138
What the hell is going on?

746
00:34:44.449 --> 00:34:47.044
<i>A little aloe will do wonders
for that combination skin.</i>

747
00:34:49.154 --> 00:34:53.387
Circle your horses. Jules. We're
about to crack your case like an egg.

748
00:34:54.459 --> 00:34:58.226
And then we'll make
some umlauts with shallots.

749
00:34:59.564 --> 00:35:01.157
And justice.

750
00:35:03.168 --> 00:35:04.192
<i>(BELL RINGS)</i>

751
00:35:04.269 --> 00:35:05.862
Please take your seats!

752
00:35:05.937 --> 00:35:10.375
Good. I'm glad you're all on time
for Phsysics 2: The Wrath of Kahn.

753
00:35:11.943 --> 00:35:14.777
Today's lecture will
cover comeuppance

754
00:35:14.846 --> 00:35:17.042
and how to solve a
crime in a crowded room.

755
00:35:18.450 --> 00:35:21.614
Someone here is living a lie.

756
00:35:21.686 --> 00:35:25.282
Someone in this room
is a ghost-faced killer.

757
00:35:30.261 --> 00:35:31.923
It's not you.

758
00:35:31.997 --> 00:35:34.626
But you have to do something
about the hair. immediately. Okay?

759
00:35:34.699 --> 00:35:36.634
I'd start now.

760
00:35:36.701 --> 00:35:40.160
You. Your heart is pure.

761
00:35:40.238 --> 00:35:44.073
I'd say lose the earring. but
I actually think he pulls it off.

762
00:35:46.611 --> 00:35:49.410
But you! Yeah.

763
00:35:49.481 --> 00:35:51.677
Why do they always run?

764
00:35:51.750 --> 00:35:54.549
Don't they know it
makes them look guilty?

765
00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:56.981
You need this guy?

766
00:35:57.055 --> 00:35:59.115
Thank you. Detective Lassiter.

767
00:35:59.190 --> 00:36:01.091
Have a seat.

768
00:36:02.027 --> 00:36:03.471
You mind telling us
what we're doing here?

769
00:36:03.495 --> 00:36:08.627
Well. as the beautiful. industrious
Detective O'Hara has already gathered...

770
00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:10.669
You're not the real
Kirk Gödel. are you?

771
00:36:10.735 --> 00:36:12.567
Will the real Kirk
Gödel please stand up?

772
00:36:12.637 --> 00:36:14.265
I don't think that's
gonna happen.

773
00:36:14.339 --> 00:36:15.967
You stole the real
Kirk Gödel's identity

774
00:36:16.041 --> 00:36:17.551
so that you could
get into this school.

775
00:36:17.575 --> 00:36:18.575
(GASPS)

776
00:36:19.177 --> 00:36:21.976
But there's more to this
case than stolen identity.

777
00:36:22.047 --> 00:36:23.777
Yes.

778
00:36:23.848 --> 00:36:27.944
I'm sensing a much
darker. diabolical past.

779
00:36:28.019 --> 00:36:31.717
You did a stint in juvie for
causing someone's death.

780
00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:34.350
Fifteen years ago.

781
00:36:34.426 --> 00:36:36.725
What are you nuts?
He's a kid. True.

782
00:36:36.795 --> 00:36:39.060
So how could this
be possible. class?

783
00:36:39.130 --> 00:36:40.530
Time travel.

784
00:36:40.598 --> 00:36:43.432
He cryogenically froze himself
in order to travel to the future.

785
00:36:43.635 --> 00:36:46.799
No. He's a clone
of the original.

786
00:36:46.871 --> 00:36:49.136
You know what?
Just never mind. guys.

787
00:36:49.207 --> 00:36:52.109
Just save it for your
online role-playing.

788
00:37:01.419 --> 00:37:03.217
He's wearing makeup. Is he gay?

789
00:37:03.288 --> 00:37:04.984
No.

790
00:37:05.056 --> 00:37:08.356
(STAMMERING) Well.
maybe. I don't know.

791
00:37:08.426 --> 00:37:10.452
But the reason he's
wearing makeup

792
00:37:10.528 --> 00:37:13.020
is because he is actually 30.

793
00:37:13.098 --> 00:37:14.999
trying to pass for a teenager.

794
00:37:15.066 --> 00:37:18.468
Thirty? What kind of
moisturizer do you use?

795
00:37:18.536 --> 00:37:20.528
Class. I would
advise you. take notes.

796
00:37:20.605 --> 00:37:22.767
There will be a test on this.

797
00:37:26.478 --> 00:37:28.344
You were always the
smartest kid in your class.

798
00:37:28.413 --> 00:37:29.523
<i>but with juvie on your record.</i>

799
00:37:29.547 --> 00:37:31.516
<i>you couldn't get into college.</i>

800
00:37:31.583 --> 00:37:33.142
Then one day. you read a story

801
00:37:33.218 --> 00:37:35.153
about a 15-year-old
from your hometown

802
00:37:35.220 --> 00:37:36.984
<i>who died in a fiery car crash.</i>

803
00:37:37.055 --> 00:37:40.651
<i>And that was the
real Kirk Gödel.</i>

804
00:37:40.725 --> 00:37:43.058
<i>And you had a light-bulb moment.</i>

805
00:37:43.128 --> 00:37:46.326
<i>All your life. people thought you
were younger than you looked.</i>

806
00:37:46.397 --> 00:37:49.060
<i>so you decided to
take advantage of that</i>

807
00:37:49.134 --> 00:37:52.161
<i>and hit a huge reset
button on your life.</i>

808
00:37:52.237 --> 00:37:54.331
<i>You forged Kirk's documents.</i>

809
00:37:54.405 --> 00:37:57.432
<i>then you went online and
deleted his death certificate.</i>

810
00:37:57.509 --> 00:37:59.375
A new identity plus
your natural intelligence

811
00:37:59.444 --> 00:38:01.709
meant you were a
cinch to make Meitner.

812
00:38:01.780 --> 00:38:04.978
<i>Now you would graduate from one
of the best high schools in the country.</i>

813
00:38:05.049 --> 00:38:09.419
get a scholarship to the Ivys and
become a yuppie captain of industry.

814
00:38:09.487 --> 00:38:13.083
And it was all rolling
along beautifully until Hahn

815
00:38:13.158 --> 00:38:15.389
<i>discovered your
dirty little secret.</i>

816
00:38:15.460 --> 00:38:18.225
<i>He blackmailed you for
your scholarship stipend.</i>

817
00:38:18.296 --> 00:38:20.993
<i>He needed the money to make
a bank payment by Wednesday.</i>

818
00:38:21.065 --> 00:38:23.000
<i>Money you weren't
willing to pay.</i>

819
00:38:23.067 --> 00:38:26.834
<i>You were so distraught you
called your cousin to vent.</i>

820
00:38:26.905 --> 00:38:29.739
You decided that the only
way out was to kill Hahn

821
00:38:29.808 --> 00:38:32.243
<i>and make it look
like an accident.</i>

822
00:38:34.345 --> 00:38:40.808
Finally. you hacked in and deleted
all records that you were ever in juvie.

823
00:38:40.885 --> 00:38:43.354
Brilliant until the end.

824
00:38:43.421 --> 00:38:47.791
Well. until this last part
when you got caught

825
00:38:47.859 --> 00:38:49.953
on the wild line.

826
00:38:50.028 --> 00:38:51.519
Like a salmon.

827
00:38:55.533 --> 00:38:57.001
Pencils down!

828
00:38:58.236 --> 00:38:59.465
Come on.

829
00:39:01.239 --> 00:39:04.732
Cuff him. O'Hara.
But here. use mine.

830
00:39:05.343 --> 00:39:06.971
You've earned it.

831
00:39:07.979 --> 00:39:09.811
Anything else I need to learn?

832
00:39:09.881 --> 00:39:11.816
There's one last lesson.

833
00:39:11.883 --> 00:39:15.650
Forget all the other lessons
and know that you're a good cop.

834
00:39:21.192 --> 00:39:24.754
You know I'm gonna need
those cuffs back. right? Good.

835
00:39:33.004 --> 00:39:34.028
Martinsdale?

836
00:39:34.105 --> 00:39:35.539
Macendale.

837
00:39:35.607 --> 00:39:37.473
Jay Macendale.

838
00:39:37.542 --> 00:39:40.102
Once we had the name. it
was pretty easy to track the rest.

839
00:39:40.178 --> 00:39:42.272
When he was 15. he
stole a car on a dare.

840
00:39:42.347 --> 00:39:43.906
accidentally
killed a pedestrian.

841
00:39:43.982 --> 00:39:45.125
And that's what
got him in juvie.

842
00:39:45.149 --> 00:39:48.051
I can't believe he passed himself
off as a teenager for this long.

843
00:39:48.119 --> 00:39:50.350
I don't know. Dad.
Slap a wig on you.

844
00:39:50.421 --> 00:39:53.289
you're a spitting image of
yourself when I was a kid.

845
00:39:53.358 --> 00:39:55.327
What is that supposed to mean?

846
00:39:55.393 --> 00:39:56.452
What's his problem?

847
00:39:56.527 --> 00:39:57.905
He finally got
ahold of his parents.

848
00:39:57.929 --> 00:39:59.488
Don't tell me it
was too expensive.

849
00:39:59.564 --> 00:40:02.295
My file said I qualified
for financial aid.

850
00:40:02.367 --> 00:40:03.528
Quality of life?

851
00:40:03.601 --> 00:40:05.934
They have 24/7
slushee machines there.

852
00:40:06.004 --> 00:40:08.473
The lockers are made with
teak. That's the strongest wood.

853
00:40:08.539 --> 00:40:11.552
These pieces look like they're hand
carved. Shawn. What's with the generosity?

854
00:40:11.576 --> 00:40:15.206
I saw you were still using the
ratty board with the plastic pieces.

855
00:40:15.280 --> 00:40:18.114
so I went ahead and
shoplifted this for you.

856
00:40:18.850 --> 00:40:20.648
I'm kidding. I bought it.

857
00:40:20.718 --> 00:40:23.278
Those kid geniuses
turned me on to a great IPO.

858
00:40:23.354 --> 00:40:24.354
Now. remember.

859
00:40:24.422 --> 00:40:26.516
I win. I get the
truck for a week.

860
00:40:26.591 --> 00:40:30.528
All right. How about I win.
you wash the truck for a week.

861
00:40:30.595 --> 00:40:32.406
Yeah. I don't really
understand what that means.

862
00:40:32.430 --> 00:40:33.841
I'm out there in a
pair of jean shorts...

863
00:40:33.865 --> 00:40:36.164
Shawn. focus. continuously
washing the vehicle...

864
00:40:36.234 --> 00:40:37.258
Focus.

865
00:40:37.335 --> 00:40:39.304
GUS: Too far to drive?

866
00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:42.306
You derailed my future
because Dad hates curvy roads?

867
00:40:42.373 --> 00:40:44.501
I could've been the
next Wittgenstein!

868
00:40:44.575 --> 00:40:47.101
I never got carsick
a day in my life.

869
00:40:48.446 --> 00:40:50.210
Gus doesn't deal very
well with surprises.

870
00:40:50.281 --> 00:40:52.045
GUS: I'll talk to
you later. Mom!

871
00:40:52.116 --> 00:40:54.745
You never told him I was the
one who ran over his dog. did you?

872
00:40:54.819 --> 00:40:56.549
Dad. no!

873
00:40:56.621 --> 00:40:58.419
One thing at a time.

874
00:40:59.157 --> 00:41:01.490
Thank God that dog was 17.

875
00:41:03.428 --> 00:41:04.760
Checkmate.

876
00:41:17.175 --> 00:41:20.771
<i>In between the lines
there's a lot of obscurity</i>

877
00:41:20.845 --> 00:41:24.304
<i>I'm not inclined to
resign to maturity</i>

878
00:41:24.382 --> 00:41:27.546
<i>If it's all right then
you're all wrong</i>

879
00:41:27.618 --> 00:41:31.248
<i>But why bounce around
to the same damn song</i>

880
00:41:32.390 --> 00:41:36.452
<i>You'd rather run
when you can't crawl</i>

881
00:41:38.596 --> 00:41:42.055
<i>I know. you know That
I'm not telling the truth</i>

882
00:41:42.133 --> 00:41:45.194
<i>I know. you know They
just don't have any proof</i>

883
00:41:45.269 --> 00:41:48.433
<i>Embrace the deception
Learn how to bend</i>

884
00:41:48.506 --> 00:41:52.500
<i>Your worst inhibitions tend
to psych you out in the end</i>

885
00:41:52.577 --> 00:41:54.273
<i>I know. you know</i>

886
00:41:56.180 --> 00:41:57.808
<i>I know. you know</i>
